<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,818,1804]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,350,938,964]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Description.</emphasis>
(From 
<bibRefCitation author="Martin, W. E." box="[437,585,938,964]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="1 - 5" refId="ref60537" refString="Martin, W. E. (1975) Hydrichthys pietschi, new species, (Coelenterata) parasitic on the fish, Ceratias holboelli. Bulletin of the Southern California Academy of Sciences, 74, 1 - 5." type="journal article" year="1975">Martin 1975</bibRefCitation>
, with measurements in microns): “ Polyps project from basal plate, some bearing buds on the aboral half of body… Polyp 490–1010 long, 112–168 wide. Ectoderm thin (about 3) endoderm 809 thick enclosing many granules 0.8–. 
<quantity box="[790,842,1018,1044]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.286" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" unit="in" value="9.0">9 in</quantity>
diameter. Nematocysts and mesoglea not seen. Medusa bud … stalked, 87–106 long, 58 wide. Mass of cells at distal end probably developing manubrium. Bud endoderm also contains granules. Bud stalk 40–50 long; 47 wide.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,818,1804]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
Basal plate …approximately 
<quantity box="[545,642,1138,1164]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2192" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" unit="in" value="4.8">4,800 in</quantity>
diam. with outer thin, 3, and inner thick, 16–22, ectoderm. Thickened inner ectoderm contains granules and may function in digestion … Endoderm thickness 8–25, with numerous granules, encloses shallow gastrovascular cavity. Maximum plate thickness 137 … about equal to the greatest penetration into the host. In this penetration the pigmented epidermis and some of the underlying tissues of the host are eroded. The granules of the hydroid and of the host epidermis are very nearly the same size. Possibly the hydroid obtains its granules from the host. There is a definite tissue response of the host to the parasite with a massing of cells beneath the inner ectoderm.… which is not seen in uninfected skin…”
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,818,1804]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,319,1418,1444]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Martin, W. E." box="[333,498,1418,1444]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="1 - 5" refId="ref60537" refString="Martin, W. E. (1975) Hydrichthys pietschi, new species, (Coelenterata) parasitic on the fish, Ceratias holboelli. Bulletin of the Southern California Academy of Sciences, 74, 1 - 5." type="journal article" year="1975">Martin (1975)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martin" authorityYear="1975" box="[623,864,1419,1444]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Hydrichthyidae" genus="Hydrichthys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="pietschi">
<emphasis box="[623,864,1419,1444]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Hydrichthys pietschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a parasite on the myctophid fish 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kroyer" authorityYear="1845" class="Actinopterygii" family="Ceratiidae" genus="Ceratias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lophiiformes" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="holboelli">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Ceratias holboelli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from waters off Oahu. It is known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[815,865,1458,1484]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">type</typeStatus>
locality, and only from the original description. This parasitic species was reported to lack both nematocysts and mesoglea. It would be remarkable indeed if nematocysts are completely lacking in polyps of this cnidarian, and the claim needs verification. While not found elsewhere on the polyp, euryteles and desmonemes were reported from the mouth region in a species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fewkes" authorityYear="1887" box="[151,294,1619,1644]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Hydrichthyidae" genus="Hydrichthys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,294,1619,1644]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Hydrichthys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[366,593,1618,1644]" name="Papua New Guinea" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Papua New Guinea</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Boero, F. &amp; Bouillon, J. &amp; Gravili, C." box="[608,876,1618,1644]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="189 - 199" refId="ref50675" refString="Boero, F., Bouillon, J. &amp; Gravili, C. (1991) The life cycle of Hydrichthys mirus (Cnidaria: Hydrozoa: Anthomedusae: Pandeidae). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 101, 189 - 199." type="journal article" year="1991">
Boero 
<emphasis box="[689,740,1619,1644]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">et al</emphasis>
. 1991: 191
</bibRefCitation>
). While scarce or sometimes apparently absent, nematocysts have also been reported in hydroids of both 
<taxonomicName authority="(Jungersen, 1911)" baseAuthorityName="Jungersen" baseAuthorityYear="1911" box="[828,1206,1658,1684]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Hydrichthyidae" genus="Hydrichthys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="sarcotretis">
<emphasis box="[828,988,1659,1684]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">H. sarcotretis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Jungersen, H. F. E." box="[1005,1198,1658,1684]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="1 - 38" refId="ref58757" refString="Jungersen, H. F. E. (1911) On a new gymnoblastic hydroid (Ichthyocodium sarcotretis) epizoic on a new parasitic copepod (Sarcotretes scopeli) infesting Scopelus glacialis Rhdt. Videnskabelige Meddelelser fra Dansk Naturhistorisk Forening, 64, 1 - 38. [Dating of this work follows Vervoort 1995]" type="journal article" year="1911">Jungersen, 1911</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Damas, 1934" authorityName="Damas" authorityYear="1934" class="Hydrozoa" family="Hydrichthyidae" genus="Hydrichthys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="cyclothonis">
<emphasis box="[1266,1436,1659,1684]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">H. cyclothonis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Damas, H." box="[151,305,1698,1724]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="1 - 10" refId="ref54626" refString="Damas, H. (1934) Hydrichthys cyclothonis (nov. sp.), hydroide parasite du poisson Cyclothone signata (Garman). Bulletin du Musee Royal d'Histoire Naturelle de Belgique, 10 (7), 1 - 10." type="journal article" year="1934">Damas, 1934</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from Europe (Jungersen 1913; 
<bibRefCitation author="Schuchert, P." box="[677,865,1698,1724]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="195 - 396" refId="ref64567" refString="Schuchert, P. (2007) The European athecate hydroids and their medusae (Hydrozoa, Cnidaria): Filifera Part 2. Revue Suisse de Zoologie, 114, 195 - 396." type="journal article" year="2007">Schuchert 2007</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
